\pard\keepn\nowidctlpar\sb120\sa120\sl240\slmult0\tx0\cf0\b\f1 1.4\tab Component Class Overview\f0\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\li720\sa120\f1 LoginActions\b0 : \par
LoginActions defines login and logout actions for this component.\par
Login action is responsible for logging in the user to the application,\par
Logout action is responsible for logging out the user.\par
If any exception occurs in both action methods, resource key should be added to the ActionMessage.\par
Since all the exceptions will be caught in both methods, Logger is employed to log any caught exception. Note that log mechanism is optional.\par
This class is thread safe.\par
\par
\b SecurityManagerAuthenticator\b0 : \par
This class is used to authenticate user. The authentication work will be delegated to the LoginBean. The login bean will be retrieved from the JNDI Context by the bean name.\f0\par
\f1 This class is thread safe since it does not contain any mutable inner state.\f0\par
\f1\par
\b AuthResponseParser\b0  \par
This interface defines the contract of keeping the track of the log state stored in the request or session. The setLoginState method is used to set the user log state (failed or succeeded). The unsetLoginState method is used to unset the user log state.\par
In order to integrate other authenticator implementation into this component, application user must also provide the corresponding implementation of this interface to manage the log states.\par
The implementation of this interface is required to be thread safe.\par
\par
\b SecurityManagerAuthResponseParser\b0 : \par
This class is used to manage the log state in request for the SecurityManagerAuthenticator, so it\rquote s expected that Response#getDetails() should return com.topcoder.security.TCSubject.\par
In the setLoginState method, if authentication succeeded, it will store in the user identifier in the session identifier.\par
In the unsetLoginState method, it will remove the user identifier from the session and invalidate the session.\par
\par
This class is thread safe since it does not contain any mutable state.\f0\par
\par
